WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.160
All right, welcome everybody. I will be talking about Styling and Templating Quarto Documents.

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:19.959
Once I realized that I would be the last talk of the day, I decided to employ an alternative,

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:27.400
more bust-feat style title to hopefully bring up some spirits. So it's, are you worried

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:34.200
about styling taking too much of your time? In 20 minutes, you won't anymore. So that's

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:37.400
the general idea of what I will be talking about.

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:45.400
All right, so to set a little bit of a ground floor, I'm imagining that you, all the viewers,

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:56.000
you're either a Quarto user or you're curious about the new fancy Quarto ecosystem. If you're

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
using Quarto, then you automatically have point two, that is, you're able to create

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:08.599
a bunch of different types of documents. And you also haven't ventured into styling yet,

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:15.400
because this is a talk about how to style. So imagine you're doing a weekly report at

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:23.800
work and some of the higher-ups want you to use the corporate theme. This might not resonate

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:29.400
with you, so we can pop out some of these things. So instead of weekly reports, it should

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:38.000
be, write a slideshow for positive times. Higher-ups should be yourself. And corporate

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:48.000
design should be water-tolerant CETL theme. But really, as long as you can mix and match

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:58.199
until it aligns with what is happening in your life. So what I see, and I felt this

00:01:58.199 --> 00:02:07.000
too, is styling is incredibly daunting because there's so much happening and there's so many

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.199
people that are so much greater at it than I will ever be. And you think, this is taking

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:19.600
forever, and it could take forever. And what I'm hoping that you will take away from this

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:27.399
talk is that it doesn't have to be. I have the opposite problem right now, is that I

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:37.600
just spent too much time writing slides. But the same principles still hold, that to create

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:44.199
beautiful products, you don't need a lot. You can get very far with just a little bit.

00:02:44.199 --> 00:02:51.800
And personal advice, I time-block myself with styling, so whenever I do slides, I set aside

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:57.600
time first to figure out the theme, and then once that's done, I write content and then

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:04.000
I never touch the theme, unless there's a little critical error. So with little effort,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
we can do quite a lot. And in this talk, I'll talk about the main three things. So

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.399
I'll talk about how just by changing the color, font, and size of the different elements in

00:03:15.399 --> 00:03:24.800
your total output, you can do quite a lot. So how do you write a theme? We've already

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:30.800
seen a couple of people have talked about this so far. And it will depend on the format

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:39.000
you're using. So if you have some HTML document or website, you need to use CSS, maybe some

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.800
JavaScript if you're fancy. PowerPoint has a whole different way of setting things up.

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:51.000
LaTeX also has a whole different way of setting things up. So every type of input is slightly

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.399
different, but the general idea is the same. And the total website has the documentation

00:03:57.399 --> 00:04:03.399
of where to find everything. For the rest of the talk, I will assume you know what you

00:04:03.399 --> 00:04:17.100
want. So I won't be talking about how to find the perfect font and perfect color palette

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:22.000
and how to do all of that because we simply don't have the time.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:31.600
So here is a very simple, well, this is the default HTML page for Toro that comes up when

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:36.600
you just start a studio, add new thing. So here on the left-hand side, we just have it.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:43.000
And it looks like how we expect. We have headers coming up. We have plain text. We have toad.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.500
It prints out as well. Main thing is we have a little format up here. And on the right-hand

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:59.700
side, we see how it looks once it has been rendered. To be able to employ theming for HTML,

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:05.600
the only thing we have to do, well, there's two things. First, we need to tell the document,

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:13.200
I want to use this style template. So we set theme and then specify in the theme.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:20.100
You can technically add multiple if you want. And since it's CSS, we have to test it in

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:26.399
stylesheet so it will just know, put them all together and use whatever is most recent.

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:36.899
Once we have that, we generate the corresponding CSS document. For Toro to be able to use

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:49.700
this properly, we need these comments to denote that this is a proper CSS file and different

00:05:49.700 --> 00:05:57.200
things should be placed roughly in these different places. But it shouldn't quite matter where

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:03.700
you put it. But generally, you put any... You see just that slide right here.

00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:10.399
So the way I do it is I'm very opinionated in the way I create my stylesheets. And you will see

00:06:10.399 --> 00:06:16.100
that if you look on GitHub what I have. I always start by generating my color palette.

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:22.700
And I always name it with $theme- and then the human readable name of the color.

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:29.399
So here, I'm creating a black, a white, and a teal and a blue just because we need some colors.

00:06:29.399 --> 00:06:35.500
It doesn't have any deeper meaning about it. In general advice, when you're doing any kind of theming,

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:44.100
whether it be for fun or for corporate use, you don't want too many. You can do a lot with one,

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:51.299
two colors, maybe three. But once you start adding more, you get some dilution of it.

00:06:52.299 --> 00:07:00.000
Another thing you might have noticed is I have my black and white that I'm using.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:08.600
But the black isn't the blackest black possible. I'm using a very gray but not all the way black.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:19.200
And that's simply because completely pitch black text on completely white background is very straining for the eyes.

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:28.399
So just reducing a little bit of the contrast is pleasant without you really noticing that it's a thing.

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:32.600
You still need a high enough contrast that you can actually see what's happening.

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:37.700
But generally, going a little bit down. And the reverse is true as well.

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:46.600
So you don't want white, white text on a dark background. Try to pinch a little bit to there.

00:07:46.799 --> 00:07:58.299
And with the colors, they should be different. There's a million tools online of how to find contrast, colorblind friendliness.

00:07:58.299 --> 00:08:02.799
So once we have these defined, I have four or five up here at the top,

00:08:02.799 --> 00:08:08.299
then we can use those variables and specify these SAS variables.

00:08:08.299 --> 00:08:13.299
So we see here we have body slash background.

00:08:13.299 --> 00:08:20.000
Toro will see that and turn the right element on the document into that color.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.399
And there's a bunch of built-in SAS variables. They're all in the footer link.

00:08:25.399 --> 00:08:31.700
So we just specify those down and we're using the theme we see at the top.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:38.500
Sometimes there's some styling that can't be accomplished simply by using the SAS variables.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:42.500
That's why we use the rule. So this is just plain CSS.

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:50.000
But it's the SCSS variant, so we are allowed to do a little bit of math and manipulations.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:59.500
So you will see in my H1 header, which is the main header in the document, I'm using this dot and function right here.

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:03.799
So I'm saying take this color and make it 50% darker.

00:09:03.799 --> 00:09:09.799
So we don't have a million head totes everywhere that might be slightly related.

00:09:09.799 --> 00:09:14.799
There's multiple colors in our document, but we only have two base colors.

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:21.099
And you can get quite far with this, and it's generally a good idea if you can,

00:09:21.099 --> 00:09:23.200
maybe you can use this darkening and lightening thing.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:29.400
So have some coherent theme to it.

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:32.200
Changing the font is just the same.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:39.099
Since we're working with HTML, we can use some Google font setup to pull in the fonts we like.

00:09:39.099 --> 00:09:49.299
And then we have SCSS variables, just the same, to set the variables, to specify things,

00:09:49.299 --> 00:09:53.099
and Tor will just know what to do, make everything happen.

00:09:53.099 --> 00:09:57.700
And lastly, sizing.

00:09:57.700 --> 00:10:00.000
I'm a broken record by now.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.500
You set them up as SCSS variables.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:09.799
There is this great idea of the font size of the root.

00:10:09.799 --> 00:10:15.900
So this is just the size of the main text of the document.

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:18.299
You set that.

00:10:18.299 --> 00:10:27.400
But then, most every styling of the rest of the document is computed as a function of this root.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:32.700
So the h1 header normally defaults to two and a half times the root.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:35.599
h2 is two times, and so on, and so on.

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:42.700
Tote also has a change in...

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:50.900
Here, we could have stopped by just changing the root size, but I decided to show, as well,

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:59.599
we can also use our variables, then, with a little bit of math to create a more coherent theme.

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:08.400
And because there isn't a SCSS variable to control the way, the sizing of the tote,

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:13.400
you can also manually find those and create them.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:18.299
A general tip I would use is look at what other people are doing,

00:11:18.299 --> 00:11:21.599
because someone has probably run into this before,

00:11:21.599 --> 00:11:25.200
and you should steal that an artist to figure out, oh, they're doing something neat.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.400
Let me take that.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:30.599
And so we have a document right here, and it looks really nice.

00:11:30.599 --> 00:11:36.799
And to really bring up how nice it looks, I want to show the original we worked with.

00:11:36.799 --> 00:11:41.500
So by just doing a couple of very small modifications,

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:46.099
we are seeing that our document have a whole new life.

00:11:46.099 --> 00:11:55.500
And I would argue that all the transformations we can do here can be done by yourself in an hour,

00:11:55.500 --> 00:11:56.299
maybe even less.

00:11:56.299 --> 00:11:59.000
Once you get used to it, it takes 10 minutes,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:03.900
because you just take the file, change the values, and you're done.

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:05.599
So we did it.

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:13.900
We made a theme, and we're happy, and we realize, oh, this isn't just a one-time thing.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:18.299
I want to be able to use this theme over and over again.

00:12:18.299 --> 00:12:20.799
I want other people to use it over and over again.

00:12:20.799 --> 00:12:22.500
What do I do?

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:28.400
So this is where we bring in the idea of a total template.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:33.200
So there's this great tweet by David Robinson, and I'll read it for you right now.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:38.900
It says, when you've written the same code three times, write a function.

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:44.599
When you've given the same in-person advice three times, write a blog post.

00:12:44.599 --> 00:12:50.299
And I would take the honor of extending this.

00:12:50.299 --> 00:12:57.299
So when you're needing the same styling three times, write a total template.

00:12:57.299 --> 00:13:04.000
And I'll argue it takes less time to do the total template than it is to write an R function

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.200
or to write a blog post.

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:09.900
So creating a template.

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:12.299
We start by creating a data repository.

00:13:12.299 --> 00:13:17.200
It isn't technically necessary, but we start by creating a project right here.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.200
This is what it would look like.

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:25.099
We have our index.tomd, which is what I normally use as my base name,

00:13:25.099 --> 00:13:28.599
and we have our styles, and we have a bunch of other things that happen

00:13:28.599 --> 00:13:34.900
when we create a studio project.

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:42.000
The first thing we do is we rename the main document we're working with to template.tomd.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.700
That lets Tor know that this is the file that is the base of the template.

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:48.799
That's the one that needs to be copied over.

00:13:48.799 --> 00:13:50.299
And we're done.

00:13:50.299 --> 00:13:52.000
We made a template.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.700
Now, if this is on GitHub, you can use the terminal command,

00:13:56.700 --> 00:14:03.099
quarter use template, the name of the GitHub repository,

00:14:03.099 --> 00:14:09.799
and this file structure will be copied over to wherever loader you point it to.

00:14:09.799 --> 00:14:13.099
And the template is what's being used.

00:14:13.099 --> 00:14:16.400
It will ignore hidden files by default.

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:19.500
So it won't copy over the R history, the dig files,

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:22.799
or all the things you normally don't want to be copied over anyway.

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:28.200
And if there's other things you don't want, like the RStudio project file,

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:34.099
we can use this .totalignore file added in here

00:14:34.099 --> 00:14:37.400
to then specify where it's to say,

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:42.900
oh, don't use this, don't move this file over as well.

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:46.599
I said that we don't technically need a GitHub repository.

00:14:46.599 --> 00:14:50.299
Instead of GitHub organization extension,

00:14:50.299 --> 00:14:53.700
you can point it to, like, a zipped file.

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:56.099
So if it's a Torpred environment,

00:14:56.099 --> 00:15:01.000
you might not want to put the theme publicly for everyone to see.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.299
As long as the user is able to point to the zip of this file,

00:15:06.299 --> 00:15:09.299
it should all, like, to a zip of the folder,

00:15:09.299 --> 00:15:11.299
everything should work out well.

00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:14.900
You can also, I showed a very simple here,

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:19.000
but you can use, put other things in it.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.799
Here, the template is just whatever document you have.

00:15:21.799 --> 00:15:24.200
You could put boilerplate in there as well.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:26.799
So you can really put whatever is in,

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:32.599
like, the useTemplate function is, in a way, just a copy-paste.

00:15:32.599 --> 00:15:37.200
But it allows you to reuse the same things over and over again.

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.500
All right, that is all I have.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:44.200
I hope you create pretty things before I let you all go.

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:46.700
I want to point you towards the Twitter documentation.

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:49.599
So twitter.org, it's great.

00:15:49.599 --> 00:15:52.799
If you go on GitHub, there's already, like,

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:57.099
dozens and dozens of templates for you to use.

00:15:57.099 --> 00:16:01.200
And on my personal blog, on the third link,

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:04.200
I created this thing called Slidecraft 101,

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:11.500
where I try to tell you how to make fun things with slides.

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:13.599
And I've done three in a year,

00:16:13.599 --> 00:16:15.799
so it's going slow.

00:16:15.799 --> 00:16:18.799
Thank you.

00:16:18.799 --> 00:16:25.799
APPLAUSE

00:16:25.799 --> 00:16:27.599
Thank you.

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:30.599
We have a couple of questions, and we have time, too.

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:35.000
So first one, what advice would you have for those of us

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.700
that are perfectionists and that need to let go

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:43.500
and spend less time styling, but you just struggle doing so?

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:46.099
Oh, so brilliant question.

00:16:46.099 --> 00:16:49.500
So by default, you're never done styling.

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:51.200
Like, there's always more to do.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:53.700
So I would suggest, like, the time blocking,

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:56.200
to do the high-priority items first,

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:00.400
and then say, I have two hours, or I have four hours.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:03.599
I time block myself to one days of work.

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:06.099
So I say, like, on the 25th, I style,

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:07.699
and then I won't style anymore.

00:17:07.699 --> 00:17:11.599
And then I might be sad because I couldn't do anything,

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:16.900
everything I needed, but that's how you have to do it.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:18.500
You kind of answered the second question,

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:20.300
which is, what's your self-imposed time limit

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:22.000
for creating a theme?

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.599
Yes, so slide themes, one day.

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:32.300
LAUGHTER

